Something Ive been thinking about lately is how theres a weird symmetry between mainstream economics and Austrian economics

Austrians believe that central banks encourage shortterm overconsumption at the expense of longterm sustainable growth But they dont make a distinction between savings and investment All postponement of consumption is equally good and prudent
To an Austrian saving your money or keeping a pile of gold in your backyard is per se good for the long term even if that money isnt being put to use for anything productive

The mainstream essentially just flips this view on its head Excessive saving is per se a problem that negative rates are meant to help solve but there doesnt seem to be much of a distinction between speculative investment actual investment or consumption
To my point this is a common view in Austrian circles
Nonetheless hoarding and investing are separate things and too often theyre conflated
